The code begins with <!DOCTYPE html>. This line declares that the document is written in HTML5. It tells the browser to render the page in standards mode, ensuring that modern HTML rules are applied correctly.

Next comes the <html lang="en"> element. The <html> tag is the root element of the entire webpage. Everything on the page is contained inside it. The attribute lang="en" specifies that the language of the document is English. This is important for accessibility tools like screen readers and also helps search engines understand the content.

Inside the <html> element, the first major section is <head>. The head contains metadata, which is information about the webpage that is not directly visible on the page itself. The line <meta charset="UTF-8"> defines the character encoding as UTF-8. This ensures that special characters, such as accented letters, are displayed correctly. The next line, <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">, controls how the page is displayed on different devices. It ensures that the layout adapts properly to mobile screens, making the page responsive. The <title> element sets the title of the webpage, which appears in the browser tab. In this case, the title is “Horace Englossed.”

After the head section, the <body> element begins. The body contains all visible content of the webpage. The first element inside the body is <header>. The header usually contains introductory material, such as the website title or logo. Here, it includes an <h1> heading with the text “Horace Englossed.” The <h1> element represents the main heading of the page and should typically appear only once.

Following the header is the <nav> element. This section contains the navigation menu. Inside the navigation, there is an unordered list (<ul>). Each list item (<li>) contains a link (<a> element). The links use href attributes such as #home, #about, #services, and #contact. These are internal anchor links, meaning they are meant to link to sections within the same page that have matching id attributes. However, since no elements with these IDs exist in the code, the links currently do not lead anywhere.

Next, there is an <aside> element with the ID sidebar-controls. The <aside> tag is used for content that is related to the main content but not central to it. In this case, it represents a sidebar containing controls. Inside it, there is a heading <h2> labeled “Controls” and a list of three buttons. These buttons do not perform any action yet because no JavaScript functionality has been added. They serve as placeholders for possible interactive features.

After the first sidebar, the <main> element appears. The <main> tag defines the primary content area of the page and should only be used once per page. Inside this element, there is a secondary heading <h2> and a paragraph <p> with placeholder text. This section is intended to hold the main content of the webpage, such as a text edition, translation, or other central material.

Following the main content is a second <aside> element with the ID glossen-sidebar. This is another sidebar area meant for supplementary information. It contains a heading labeled “Glossen” and a list of glossary terms. These items are currently simple text entries and do not have interactive functionality. In a digital edition context, this section could display annotations, explanations, or commentary related to the main text.

Finally, the page ends with a <footer> element. The footer typically contains additional information such as copyright notices or legal information. In this case, it includes a paragraph with the copyright symbol, written as &copy;, followed by the year 2026 and the site name “Horace Englossed.”
